Odaily Planet Daily News According to CryptoSlam data, NFT sales fell 35.15% month-on-month to US$112.7 million this week. However, market participation has clearly increased, indicating that despite the overall lower sales, new traders are showing increasing interest:
-NFT sales fell from $119.5 million to $112.7 million;
-NFT buyers surged 624.41% to 203,994;
-NFT sellers increased 519.61% to 158,805;
-NFT transactions fell slightly by 1.41% to 1,443,007;
-Ethereum remains the market leader, but sales fell 41.25% to $56 million and the number of buyers grew 81.43% to 30,598;
-Mythos Chain ranked second with $13.9 million in sales, up 4.66%;
-Solana maintained its third position with $11 million in sales, despite a 32.56% drop;
-Polygon POL (formerly MATIC) ranked fourth with sales of $8.1 million, up 10.76%;
-Bitcoin fell to fifth with sales of $6.7 million, down 71.42%.
In terms of specific NFT series, DMarket led with sales of $8.7 million, up 7.98%. Courtyard followed closely with sales of $7.3 million, up 25.78%.
CryptoPunks ranked third with sales of $5.2 million, down 30.01%. Pudgy Penguins fell to fourth with sales of $5.1 million, down 55.29%. Azuki ranked fifth with sales of $5 million, down 79.17%.

Odaily Planet Daily News Coingecko data shows that XRP Ledger (XRPL) ecological tokens have generally risen in the past week, including: 
XRP rose 11.9% and is now at $2.79; 
Sologenic (SOLO) rose 21.6% and is now at $0.4026; 
Coreum (COREUM) rose 21.3% and is now at $0.1962. 
According to Polymarket data, the probability of XRP ETF being approved this year has risen to 80%. 
Earlier news, the SEC accepted the Grayscale XRP Trust conversion ETF application and started the review process. In addition, JPMorgan analysts reported that the spot XRP ETF could bring in up to $8 billion in institutional funds.
